WEBVTT
Kind: captions
Language: en

00:00:08.337 --> 00:00:09.920
SPEAKER 1: Hello,
Googlers and guests.

00:00:09.920 --> 00:00:13.360
My name is [INAUDIBLE] and
welcome to Talks at Google.

00:00:13.360 --> 00:00:16.690
Our guest today is the
actor Manoj Bajpayee.

00:00:16.690 --> 00:00:20.620
My earliest memories of him are
from the TV series "Swabhimaan"

00:00:20.620 --> 00:00:24.250
and watching him set
the screen on fire,

00:00:24.250 --> 00:00:26.450
as Bhiku Mhatre in "Satya."

00:00:26.450 --> 00:00:28.190
It's been nearly 20
years since then,

00:00:28.190 --> 00:00:31.600
and he has performed
many outstanding roles

00:00:31.600 --> 00:00:36.880
in movies like "Shool," "Aks,"
"Zubeidaa," "Chakravyuh,"

00:00:36.880 --> 00:00:39.130
"Aligarh," and
"Gangs of Wasseypur."

00:00:39.130 --> 00:00:42.130
His craft has been recognized.

00:00:42.130 --> 00:00:44.710
He's a two-time winner of
the National Film Award

00:00:44.710 --> 00:00:46.990
and a four-time winner
of the Filmfare Award.

00:00:46.990 --> 00:00:49.993
Please join me in welcoming
the very talented Mr. Manoj

00:00:49.993 --> 00:00:50.959
Bajpayee.

00:00:50.959 --> 00:00:54.823
[APPLAUSE]

00:00:56.155 --> 00:00:57.238
MANOJ BAJPAYEE: Thank you.

00:01:01.942 --> 00:01:03.150
SPEAKER 1: Welcome to Google.

00:01:03.150 --> 00:01:04.108
MANOJ BAJPAYEE: Thanks.

00:01:06.190 --> 00:01:08.560
SPEAKER 1: So I wanted
to start by asking--

00:01:08.560 --> 00:01:10.360
you took a tour
around the campus--

00:01:10.360 --> 00:01:12.600
is this your first
time at Google?

00:01:12.600 --> 00:01:14.960
MANOJ BAJPAYEE: This is the
first time in San Francisco.

00:01:17.865 --> 00:01:21.760
Everybody said that this
is the best city in USA.

00:01:21.760 --> 00:01:26.040
I, personally, love Europe,
as I was speaking to my friend

00:01:26.040 --> 00:01:31.420
[INAUDIBLE]---- we shared the
common thing about Europe.

00:01:31.420 --> 00:01:35.590
But yes, tonight I'm
going for a look around.

00:01:35.590 --> 00:01:37.600
Some friends are taking
me to San Francisco

00:01:37.600 --> 00:01:40.610
and all the landmark places.

00:01:40.610 --> 00:01:44.140
So yes, first time at
Google, and first time

00:01:44.140 --> 00:01:46.930
in a place which is
considered the biggest

00:01:46.930 --> 00:01:48.480
company in the world.

00:01:48.480 --> 00:01:52.320
So yes, this is quite an
interesting, exciting tour.

00:01:52.320 --> 00:01:54.730
SPEAKER 1: Thank you.

00:01:54.730 --> 00:01:57.670
I'd like to start by how
you got into show business.

00:01:57.670 --> 00:02:00.160
I've heard about the time
that you were a teenager.

00:02:00.160 --> 00:02:04.210
You moved to Delhi to apply to
the National School of Drama.

00:02:04.210 --> 00:02:05.980
You applied many times.

00:02:05.980 --> 00:02:08.560
You were rejected,
but you persevered.

00:02:08.560 --> 00:02:11.560
At such a young age,
how were you so focused

00:02:11.560 --> 00:02:12.790
on one career choice?

00:02:12.790 --> 00:02:13.960
What drew you?

00:02:13.960 --> 00:02:14.580
MANOJ BAJPAYEE: I don't know.

00:02:14.580 --> 00:02:16.038
I mean, since my
childhood I wanted

00:02:16.038 --> 00:02:23.740
to become an actor, which was
quite a rarity in a small town

00:02:23.740 --> 00:02:28.540
like mine which was quite
backward in those days,

00:02:28.540 --> 00:02:30.370
and it still is.

00:02:30.370 --> 00:02:35.550
We are working very hard towards
convincing the government of--

00:02:35.550 --> 00:02:41.230
be hard to really focus all
the developmental issues

00:02:41.230 --> 00:02:42.970
towards that area.

00:02:42.970 --> 00:02:47.470
But yes, it was a rarity.

00:02:47.470 --> 00:02:51.700
Being an actor was not
something that any parent

00:02:51.700 --> 00:02:54.300
wanted for their child to
get into that profession.

00:02:54.300 --> 00:02:56.410
It was not looked up.

00:02:56.410 --> 00:02:59.210
It was looked down by everybody.

00:02:59.210 --> 00:03:05.170
[NON-ENGLISH SPEECH]

00:03:05.170 --> 00:03:07.480
For me, it was
very, very essential

00:03:07.480 --> 00:03:12.980
to keep my dream very close to
my chest since my childhood.

00:03:12.980 --> 00:03:17.450
So I never actually told
anybody, any close friend

00:03:17.450 --> 00:03:21.530
of mine, closest of the body
that this is the dream I have,

00:03:21.530 --> 00:03:25.050
and this is what I am
planning to do in life.

00:03:25.050 --> 00:03:28.340
So it was a hard task.

00:03:28.340 --> 00:03:31.580
Dreaming of becoming an
actor was much more easier

00:03:31.580 --> 00:03:34.430
than keeping your dream
close to your heart

00:03:34.430 --> 00:03:36.050
and not letting
anyone know about it.

00:03:36.050 --> 00:03:38.580
That was very, very
difficult for me.

00:03:38.580 --> 00:03:42.770
So the 17 and a half years
that I spent in my village,

00:03:42.770 --> 00:03:49.190
or in the small town where
I was doing my schooling,

00:03:49.190 --> 00:03:52.880
I kept on looking for some
avenues where I could just

00:03:52.880 --> 00:03:57.530
go ahead and do some acting.

00:03:57.530 --> 00:03:59.750
But it was not available.

00:03:59.750 --> 00:04:02.630
It used to happen only
in the school functions

00:04:02.630 --> 00:04:07.030
sometimes, one skit
here, some skit there.

00:04:07.030 --> 00:04:10.130
Watching Amitabh Bachchan
films and imitating him

00:04:10.130 --> 00:04:12.240
in front of the mirror.

00:04:12.240 --> 00:04:17.730
These were the only
things which was available

00:04:17.730 --> 00:04:22.329
to me, where I could just
go ahead and give it a try.

00:04:22.329 --> 00:04:23.870
So for me it was
very, very important

00:04:23.870 --> 00:04:28.540
to move my base from that
small town or that village

00:04:28.540 --> 00:04:31.920
to a better place like Delhi.

00:04:31.920 --> 00:04:34.220
So I thought of
doing my graduation

00:04:34.220 --> 00:04:36.590
from Delhi, Delhi University.

00:04:36.590 --> 00:04:40.713
That was a long, long
journey for 17 years old, 17

00:04:40.713 --> 00:04:44.510
and 1/2 year old person who
has never been to any big city

00:04:44.510 --> 00:04:45.810
before.

00:04:45.810 --> 00:04:50.369
So yes, that's how it
all started for me.

00:04:50.369 --> 00:04:52.660
SPEAKER 1: So you've kept
the dream close to your heart

00:04:52.660 --> 00:04:54.780
as you were leaving from there.

00:04:54.780 --> 00:04:57.210
What did you tell your parents
as you were going to Delhi?

00:04:57.210 --> 00:04:59.220
MANOJ BAJPAYEE: The
easiest thing to tell

00:04:59.220 --> 00:05:01.760
your [NON-ENGLISH] parent
is [NON-ENGLISH SPEECH]..

00:05:01.760 --> 00:05:03.600
[LAUGHTER]

00:05:05.130 --> 00:05:07.140
The easiest way
to convince them.

00:05:07.140 --> 00:05:08.720
[NON-ENGLISH SPEECH]

00:05:09.690 --> 00:05:11.400
[LAUGHTER]

00:05:11.400 --> 00:05:13.140
My father was a
little disheartened,

00:05:13.140 --> 00:05:20.550
because he had a dream of
seeing his elder son becoming

00:05:20.550 --> 00:05:22.080
a doctor.

00:05:22.080 --> 00:05:26.116
But he said, OK, so doctor,
[NON-ENGLISH SPEECH]..

00:05:26.116 --> 00:05:29.570
[LAUGHTER]

00:05:31.366 --> 00:05:32.490
That's how I convinced him.

00:05:32.490 --> 00:05:34.890
But one thing he said
that I have six children

00:05:34.890 --> 00:05:36.510
to take care of.

00:05:36.510 --> 00:05:40.290
So I will not be very frequent
in sending money to you.

00:05:40.290 --> 00:05:42.910
So you will have to really
look after yourself,

00:05:42.910 --> 00:05:48.440
take care of yourself, of
your monthly expenditure.

00:05:48.440 --> 00:05:51.080
So sometimes he used to send
me 200 rupees, 250 rupees

00:05:51.080 --> 00:05:51.842
sometimes.

00:05:51.842 --> 00:05:53.550
But the rest of the
time I was completely

00:05:53.550 --> 00:05:56.540
dependent upon all
the friends of mine

00:05:56.540 --> 00:05:58.830
who are doing so well now.

00:05:58.830 --> 00:06:03.810
Some of them are into
income tax on a big post.

00:06:03.810 --> 00:06:10.180
One of them is the Indian
ambassador in Mexico.

00:06:10.180 --> 00:06:13.950
These friends of mine, they
took it upon themselves

00:06:13.950 --> 00:06:15.600
to look after Manoj Bajpayee.

00:06:15.600 --> 00:06:17.780
They believed in my dream.

00:06:17.780 --> 00:06:21.790
Somewhere, they felt that
[NON-ENGLISH SPEECH]..

00:06:27.540 --> 00:06:29.550
You just wear it.

00:06:29.550 --> 00:06:30.932
I have a shirt.

00:06:30.932 --> 00:06:31.890
You'll take it from me.

00:06:31.890 --> 00:06:33.250
I was very short.

00:06:33.250 --> 00:06:37.330
OK, how much you
need for your rent?

00:06:37.330 --> 00:06:38.010
100 rupees?

00:06:38.010 --> 00:06:43.830
So this month I'm putting in
on behalf of Monoj Bajpayee.

00:06:43.830 --> 00:06:49.780
So that's how I was taken
care of by all my friends.

00:06:49.780 --> 00:06:52.800
I always say that without
them, without their support,

00:06:52.800 --> 00:06:58.060
I wouldn't have survived
in a city like Delhi.

00:06:58.060 --> 00:06:59.040
SPEAKER 1: Interesting.

00:06:59.040 --> 00:07:00.050
So now you're in Delhi.

00:07:00.050 --> 00:07:02.220
You are participating
in theater.

00:07:02.220 --> 00:07:03.930
Tell us about your
early days in theatre.

00:07:03.930 --> 00:07:07.332
Is there a role or a performance
that you found particularly

00:07:07.332 --> 00:07:08.790
rewarding during
your theatre days?

00:07:08.790 --> 00:07:10.498
MANOJ BAJPAYEE: There
are many, actually.

00:07:12.300 --> 00:07:16.510
I used to work 16 hours,
18 hours in a day.

00:07:16.510 --> 00:07:20.300
I used to sleep for
five or six hours.

00:07:20.300 --> 00:07:22.890
And there were many challenges.

00:07:22.890 --> 00:07:25.560
For a person who was coming
from that kind of a place,

00:07:25.560 --> 00:07:30.650
learning good Hindi,
because everybody says

00:07:30.650 --> 00:07:34.210
[NON-ENGLISH SPEECH].

00:07:34.210 --> 00:07:36.500
[NON-ENGLISH SPEECH]

00:07:43.290 --> 00:07:45.050
So these are the languages.

00:07:45.050 --> 00:07:47.940
And my mother tongue
is [NON-ENGLISH]..

00:07:47.940 --> 00:07:52.770
Yes, my education
medium was Hindi.

00:07:52.770 --> 00:07:57.740
But all the [NON-ENGLISH] used
to do very badly in Hindi.

00:07:57.740 --> 00:08:01.200
They could hardly
manage second division.

00:08:01.200 --> 00:08:03.540
Because [NON-ENGLISH SPEECH].

00:08:03.540 --> 00:08:04.942
[LAUGHTER]

00:08:04.942 --> 00:08:06.161
[NON-ENGLISH SPEECH]

00:08:06.660 --> 00:08:08.700
[LAUGHTER]

00:08:08.700 --> 00:08:11.180
[NON-ENGLISH SPEECH]

00:08:11.180 --> 00:08:14.820
It's tricky working on Hindi.

00:08:14.820 --> 00:08:17.370
Learning English was
a big, big challenge.

00:08:17.370 --> 00:08:20.750
But somewhere I realized
when I was a 14, 15-year-old,

00:08:20.750 --> 00:08:23.760
and I was still in school, I
realized that if I have to do

00:08:23.760 --> 00:08:28.270
well in big city, in a big
city like Delhi or Bombay,

00:08:28.270 --> 00:08:34.080
and if I have to be in industry,
I should stop listening

00:08:34.080 --> 00:08:36.450
to [NON-ENGLISH SPEECH].

00:08:42.690 --> 00:08:48.860
So English was more of tool
for me than a language.

00:08:48.860 --> 00:08:52.050
So English, [NON-ENGLISH],,
Hindi [NON-ENGLISH],,

00:08:52.050 --> 00:08:56.840
or theatre [NON-ENGLISH],,
acting a craft [NON-ENGLISH],,

00:08:56.840 --> 00:09:00.090
and monthly rent [NON-ENGLISH].

00:09:00.090 --> 00:09:06.000
There were too many challenges
that I was facing in Delhi.

00:09:06.000 --> 00:09:11.370
But yes, somewhere
theaters could

00:09:11.370 --> 00:09:14.380
help me survive everything.

00:09:14.380 --> 00:09:16.140
Whenever I used
to do rehearsals,

00:09:16.140 --> 00:09:19.830
or I used to do plays--

00:09:19.830 --> 00:09:24.020
anything related to
theater or acting--

00:09:24.020 --> 00:09:25.950
somewhere I was
completely distracted

00:09:25.950 --> 00:09:30.535
from all the difficulties
that I was facing.

00:09:30.535 --> 00:09:32.410
SPEAKER 1: Languages is
an interesting point.

00:09:32.410 --> 00:09:34.190
I wanted to ask you a
question about that.

00:09:34.190 --> 00:09:36.690
You've acted in a few Tamil
and Telugu movies as well.

00:09:36.690 --> 00:09:38.190
Do you speak any
of those languages?

00:09:38.190 --> 00:09:38.981
MANOJ BAJPAYEE: No.

00:09:38.981 --> 00:09:44.660
So I've done four
films, and I decided

00:09:44.660 --> 00:09:47.780
that I will never touch them.

00:09:47.780 --> 00:09:54.260
Because not knowing language
is the biggest handicap

00:09:54.260 --> 00:09:56.540
for any actor.

00:09:56.540 --> 00:09:58.910
So whenever I'm
conducting a workshop,

00:09:58.910 --> 00:10:03.550
I always tell all the new
actors that, you guys,

00:10:03.550 --> 00:10:07.120
your Hindi's really bad.

00:10:07.120 --> 00:10:10.770
And you are not going to be
directed by Martin Scorsese

00:10:10.770 --> 00:10:16.490
and Spielberg in Bombay.

00:10:16.490 --> 00:10:18.590
You are going to
work in Hindi films.

00:10:18.590 --> 00:10:21.475
So your language has to be good.

00:10:21.475 --> 00:10:23.234
So Tamil Telugu films that--

00:10:23.234 --> 00:10:24.650
very few films
that I have done, I

00:10:24.650 --> 00:10:30.070
have realized that somewhere
I'm doing complete injustice

00:10:30.070 --> 00:10:33.400
to my profession.

00:10:33.400 --> 00:10:36.260
Where I could not understand
anything that I was saying.

00:10:36.260 --> 00:10:40.310
I was taking the prompting
working on basic emotions.

00:10:40.310 --> 00:10:43.860
Somewhere that didn't go
down very well with me.

00:10:43.860 --> 00:10:45.020
So I stopped working.

00:10:45.020 --> 00:10:48.010
And now I don't accept that.

00:10:48.010 --> 00:10:52.466
Unless someone really comes
and pays me a huge amount.

00:10:52.466 --> 00:10:53.270
[LAUGHTER]

00:10:53.270 --> 00:10:54.990
Because as an actor--

00:10:54.990 --> 00:10:57.020
as a star, you make a
lot of money in India.

00:10:57.020 --> 00:10:58.835
But as an actor, you
don't make money.

00:10:58.835 --> 00:11:02.550
[INAUDIBLE] definitely
will agree with me.

00:11:02.550 --> 00:11:05.209
[LAUGHING]

00:11:05.209 --> 00:11:07.250
SPEAKER 1: Another
interesting nugget I picked up

00:11:07.250 --> 00:11:10.400
was you've actually done
voiceover work for two

00:11:10.400 --> 00:11:11.705
animation movies as well?

00:11:11.705 --> 00:11:12.830
MANOJ BAJPAYEE: Yes, right.

00:11:12.830 --> 00:11:14.455
SPEAKER 1: How is
that as an experience

00:11:14.455 --> 00:11:15.950
when you are not actually--

00:11:15.950 --> 00:11:17.850
you just have to use
your voice to emote?

00:11:17.850 --> 00:11:18.740
MANOJ BAJPAYEE:
Yeah, I mean, I've

00:11:18.740 --> 00:11:20.810
done radio plays when
I was doing theater,

00:11:20.810 --> 00:11:22.559
because that's how we
used to earn money--

00:11:22.559 --> 00:11:24.870
200 rupees, 400 rupees,
sometimes used to make.

00:11:24.870 --> 00:11:28.310
And I didn't find it any
different from radio plays.

00:11:28.310 --> 00:11:30.650
Because even in radio
plays those days,

00:11:30.650 --> 00:11:31.940
[NON-ENGLISH SPEECH].

00:11:37.010 --> 00:11:39.610
Or you would start working on
it, and say it in front of--

00:11:39.610 --> 00:11:41.390
now you act it out in
front of the camera.

00:11:41.390 --> 00:11:44.640
And this is what I have done
in those animation films.

00:11:44.640 --> 00:11:46.940
In one, I played Rama.

00:11:46.940 --> 00:11:49.940
In one, I played Yudhisthir.

00:11:49.940 --> 00:11:53.930
So whatever interpretation
that I have of Rama--

00:11:53.930 --> 00:11:58.100
because I always see him as
a human being, not as God--

00:11:58.100 --> 00:12:02.820
but God is [NON-ENGLISH SPEECH].

00:12:02.820 --> 00:12:05.470
But Ramji was married.

00:12:05.470 --> 00:12:09.260
Ramji went through difficulties
that all humans go through.

00:12:09.260 --> 00:12:14.780
So I treated him very
realistically for the animation

00:12:14.780 --> 00:12:16.830
film.

00:12:16.830 --> 00:12:19.360
SPEAKER 1: So you've worked
with many different directors.

00:12:19.360 --> 00:12:21.290
I'm sure each one of
them has their own style.

00:12:21.290 --> 00:12:24.360
You've worked across genres.

00:12:24.360 --> 00:12:26.540
Is there any
incident you remember

00:12:26.540 --> 00:12:28.202
where you were
concerned about working

00:12:28.202 --> 00:12:29.660
with a particular
director, and you

00:12:29.660 --> 00:12:31.130
found that as you
started working

00:12:31.130 --> 00:12:33.144
you had instant rapport?

00:12:33.144 --> 00:12:35.060
MANOJ BAJPAYEE: I get
along with my directors,

00:12:35.060 --> 00:12:37.970
because I really feel that
theater is actor's medium,

00:12:37.970 --> 00:12:40.460
and cinema is director's medium.

00:12:40.460 --> 00:12:42.450
Because he is the
only one who has

00:12:42.450 --> 00:12:45.600
complete clarity
about the entire film.

00:12:45.600 --> 00:12:48.710
So you just listen to-- you
work along with the director.

00:12:48.710 --> 00:12:51.950
You don't work separately
from the director.

00:12:55.760 --> 00:12:58.230
You are not somebody who is--

00:12:58.230 --> 00:13:06.120
are the people who are seen
when audience is watching,

00:13:06.120 --> 00:13:08.620
but it's the director
who is calling the shots.

00:13:08.620 --> 00:13:11.780
So all the people
that I worked with,

00:13:11.780 --> 00:13:16.100
I never had any issues with any
director in my entire career.

00:13:16.100 --> 00:13:19.670
I think also because
that somewhere deep down

00:13:19.670 --> 00:13:21.800
in my heart, I
feel that I am what

00:13:21.800 --> 00:13:25.130
I am because of the belief and
the faith of some directors

00:13:25.130 --> 00:13:30.720
who somehow had the vision
of taking me in those roles.

00:13:30.720 --> 00:13:33.816
SPEAKER 1: So you mentioned that
theater is an actor's medium.

00:13:33.816 --> 00:13:35.190
One of the things
one reads about

00:13:35.190 --> 00:13:38.490
is you're called upon
as the pioneering method

00:13:38.490 --> 00:13:41.400
actor in Hindi cinema,
and other actors

00:13:41.400 --> 00:13:43.020
look to you for inspiration.

00:13:43.020 --> 00:13:45.270
Do you see yourself
as a method actor?

00:13:45.270 --> 00:13:46.740
What is your style?

00:13:46.740 --> 00:13:49.230
MANOJ BAJPAYEE: Method
is something that you--

00:13:49.230 --> 00:13:50.980
you can't have one method.

00:13:50.980 --> 00:13:54.000
Yes, when you're doing
theater, you are really--

00:13:54.000 --> 00:13:55.830
you are working on yourself.

00:13:55.830 --> 00:13:59.280
You are acquiring new
skill for approaching

00:13:59.280 --> 00:14:00.880
each and every role.

00:14:00.880 --> 00:14:02.580
But at the end of
the day, when I'm

00:14:02.580 --> 00:14:06.530
working with-- on
Anurag Kashyap,

00:14:06.530 --> 00:14:10.980
I'm applying a different
way of approaching my roles.

00:14:10.980 --> 00:14:12.547
When I'm working
with Neeraj Pandey,

00:14:12.547 --> 00:14:13.630
he's completely different.

00:14:13.630 --> 00:14:18.120
He's 360 degree opposite
to Anurag Kashyap.

00:14:18.120 --> 00:14:21.810
So an actor has to
be skilled enough

00:14:21.810 --> 00:14:26.640
to really adjust his method
or approach according

00:14:26.640 --> 00:14:29.166
to the director's need.

00:14:29.166 --> 00:14:31.540
Neeraj Pandey doesn't want
you to get into the character.

00:14:31.540 --> 00:14:33.081
He just wants you
to learn your lines

00:14:33.081 --> 00:14:35.910
and come in front of
the camera and just

00:14:35.910 --> 00:14:37.680
listen to his direction.

00:14:37.680 --> 00:14:38.820
That's it.

00:14:38.820 --> 00:14:41.970
Anurag Kashyap says, you
go through your script,

00:14:41.970 --> 00:14:44.390
and you throw the script.

00:14:44.390 --> 00:14:46.830
And after that, whatever
you are going to do,

00:14:46.830 --> 00:14:47.820
I'm going to accept it.

00:14:47.820 --> 00:14:55.080
Unless it is really, really
not right for the vision

00:14:55.080 --> 00:14:56.490
that I have.

00:14:56.490 --> 00:15:02.670
So a true actor is somebody
who is never questioning

00:15:02.670 --> 00:15:07.310
the director's vision and
always ready to adjust

00:15:07.310 --> 00:15:10.070
with the director's need.

00:15:10.070 --> 00:15:14.866
So we apply different
kind of method

00:15:14.866 --> 00:15:17.490
for different kind of directors
and different kinds of scripts.

00:15:20.170 --> 00:15:22.310
SPEAKER 1: Your recent
movie, "Aligarh"--

00:15:22.310 --> 00:15:27.020
you played Professor Siras'
character as very sensitive,

00:15:27.020 --> 00:15:28.110
heartbreaking.

00:15:28.110 --> 00:15:30.940
How did you prepare for that?

00:15:30.940 --> 00:15:34.010
MANOJ BAJPAYEE: I went
the other way round.

00:15:34.010 --> 00:15:38.040
And actually, my wife was
very, very supportive.

00:15:38.040 --> 00:15:42.890
She has to keep my little
daughter in check all the time

00:15:42.890 --> 00:15:46.790
and just making sure that she
doesn't come and disturb me

00:15:46.790 --> 00:15:48.920
when I was taking
Marathi lessons, lessons

00:15:48.920 --> 00:15:52.050
from the chief
assistant director.

00:15:52.050 --> 00:15:52.790
He was very good.

00:15:52.790 --> 00:15:56.420
His knowledge about Marathi
poetry and literature

00:15:56.420 --> 00:15:58.760
was amazing.

00:15:58.760 --> 00:16:00.330
So he used to come to my place.

00:16:00.330 --> 00:16:02.260
And we should just learn--

00:16:02.260 --> 00:16:04.910
I was just learning Marathi.

00:16:04.910 --> 00:16:06.410
And this chief of
assistant director

00:16:06.410 --> 00:16:09.320
was always amazed and surprised
as to why I'm learning Marathi,

00:16:09.320 --> 00:16:11.690
because I'm not going to
say any line in Marathi

00:16:11.690 --> 00:16:14.360
in a Hindi film.

00:16:14.360 --> 00:16:18.620
But I kept on asking
him to introduce me

00:16:18.620 --> 00:16:20.600
to Marathi poetry,
Marathi poets.

00:16:20.600 --> 00:16:22.730
So he used to put it on
the YouTube sometime.

00:16:22.730 --> 00:16:26.510
He used to get some link,
open it on his computer.

00:16:26.510 --> 00:16:29.540
And I used to just listen
to those Marathi words.

00:16:29.540 --> 00:16:33.580
And sometime, I should start
writing in Marathi, also,

00:16:33.580 --> 00:16:38.320
whatever he was
asking him to write.

00:16:38.320 --> 00:16:42.170
Sometime he used to make
me read a few Marathi

00:16:42.170 --> 00:16:45.710
lines from a Marathi novel.

00:16:45.710 --> 00:16:51.390
But for me, it was
very, very important

00:16:51.390 --> 00:16:55.330
to think like Siras as a
Marathi literature person.

00:16:55.330 --> 00:17:02.140
Because Siras was-- his
sexuality was not his identity.

00:17:02.140 --> 00:17:05.660
Siras being a great
Marathi literature

00:17:05.660 --> 00:17:08.990
professor in "Aligarh"--
that was his identity.

00:17:08.990 --> 00:17:11.420
So I wanted to
know his identity,

00:17:11.420 --> 00:17:14.930
to get close to his
identity, to really get

00:17:14.930 --> 00:17:16.609
into the skin of the character.

00:17:16.609 --> 00:17:23.130
So if you see the film, his
love for Lata Mangeshkar,

00:17:23.130 --> 00:17:29.470
or love for Marathi poetry,
or the way he talks,

00:17:29.470 --> 00:17:33.790
the way he approaches
his literature--

00:17:33.790 --> 00:17:39.830
that makes Siras the character.

00:17:39.830 --> 00:17:41.660
Gay was secondary for me.

00:17:41.660 --> 00:17:44.020
Him being homosexual
was something very, very

00:17:44.020 --> 00:17:45.050
secondary for me.

00:17:45.050 --> 00:17:48.400
And that's how I
approached the character.

00:17:48.400 --> 00:17:51.300
SPEAKER 1: Last year, you
also had three short films

00:17:51.300 --> 00:17:52.230
I saw on YouTube--

00:17:52.230 --> 00:17:56.500
"Ouch," "Kriti," and "Taandav."

00:17:56.500 --> 00:17:58.000
What do you think
about that medium?

00:17:58.000 --> 00:18:00.470
Do you have more short
films coming out?

00:18:00.470 --> 00:18:02.330
MANOJ BAJPAYEE:
I'll be doing more.

00:18:02.330 --> 00:18:05.620
I'm just stopped for some time,
because now suddenly there

00:18:05.620 --> 00:18:09.440
are so many people are
making short films.

00:18:09.440 --> 00:18:12.890
I really feel that
actor is always

00:18:12.890 --> 00:18:19.760
in need of acting, is always
looking for an opportunity

00:18:19.760 --> 00:18:22.130
to act.

00:18:22.130 --> 00:18:24.560
And these short films are
giving you a nice getaway

00:18:24.560 --> 00:18:29.200
from the routine life
of acting in films.

00:18:29.200 --> 00:18:34.810
Just go act for a day
or two, and suddenly you

00:18:34.810 --> 00:18:36.160
put it on YouTube.

00:18:36.160 --> 00:18:38.650
And suddenly you see
so many reactions--

00:18:38.650 --> 00:18:43.810
so much equal to the reaction
when you're doing theater.

00:18:43.810 --> 00:18:46.480
It's so immediate
response you get.

00:18:46.480 --> 00:18:50.770
And that actually
excited me quite a lot,

00:18:50.770 --> 00:18:52.930
the kind of reaction
I got for "Taandav."

00:18:52.930 --> 00:18:57.440
And that made me, pushed
me towards making "Kriti."

00:18:57.440 --> 00:19:00.550
I convinced Shirish
or Neeraj Pandey

00:19:00.550 --> 00:19:03.530
to make two more
short films for me.

00:19:03.530 --> 00:19:08.560
But yes, I mean, you are also
pushing your limitations.

00:19:08.560 --> 00:19:10.870
The things that you
could not do in films,

00:19:10.870 --> 00:19:13.040
you are getting to do
in those 15 minutes.

00:19:13.040 --> 00:19:13.600
So why not?

00:19:13.600 --> 00:19:18.489
Just go ahead and give it a
try and learn some new things.

00:19:18.489 --> 00:19:20.530
SPEAKER 1: I think we have
a clip from "Taandav."

00:19:20.530 --> 00:19:22.988
Could we please play that?

