AUDIENCE: So arguably, two
of your most defining roles

00:29:12.260 --> 00:29:15.332
have been Bhiku Mhatre
and Sardar Khan, right?

00:29:15.332 --> 00:29:16.790
What are some of
the challenges you

00:29:16.790 --> 00:29:18.380
had while preparing
for these roles

00:29:18.380 --> 00:29:21.140
and bringing such
reality to screen?

00:29:24.110 --> 00:29:27.980
MANOJ BAJPAYEE: When I
was given Bhiku Mhatre,

00:29:27.980 --> 00:29:31.460
I really didn't know
how to go about it.

00:29:31.460 --> 00:29:33.950
Because just before
Bhiku Mhatre,

00:29:33.950 --> 00:29:38.090
a couple of years before
"Satya," [INAUDIBLE]

00:29:38.090 --> 00:29:42.110
is a film that left
such a huge impact

00:29:42.110 --> 00:29:44.810
on each and everybody's mind.

00:29:44.810 --> 00:29:46.550
And all the actors
were completely

00:29:46.550 --> 00:29:48.830
blown away by the performance
of Mr. [INAUDIBLE],,

00:29:48.830 --> 00:29:52.580
who I personally think
is one of India's finest.

00:29:52.580 --> 00:29:54.880
And he's never gotten his due.

00:29:57.970 --> 00:30:02.690
So when I was doing Bhiki
Mhatre, I was very scared.

00:30:02.690 --> 00:30:06.370
I always had this fear that I'm
going to have an [NON-ENGLISH]

00:30:06.370 --> 00:30:10.217
kind of a syndrome while I'll
be playing the character.

00:30:10.217 --> 00:30:11.800
So I had to go
completely against him.

00:30:11.800 --> 00:30:15.790
So to prepare the role, I
went into the back story

00:30:15.790 --> 00:30:17.050
of Bhiku Mhatre.

00:30:17.050 --> 00:30:19.150
I prepared a back story
of Bhiku Mhatre, which

00:30:19.150 --> 00:30:27.520
helped me to really sketch
out the approach or the method

00:30:27.520 --> 00:30:28.500
to do that route.

00:30:28.500 --> 00:30:32.200
So that's how Bhiku
Mhatre happened.

00:30:32.200 --> 00:30:34.000
And also, Anurag Kashyap--

00:30:34.000 --> 00:30:37.390
the script gives you a
lot of scope to improvise.

00:30:37.390 --> 00:30:40.000
And Ram those days
was very open.

00:30:40.000 --> 00:30:42.850
He said, just go ahead
and give it a try.

00:30:42.850 --> 00:30:46.180
And if it is really
wrong, I'll cut it.

00:30:46.180 --> 00:30:48.370
Otherwise, I'm going
to keep everything.

00:30:48.370 --> 00:30:52.330
So all of these guys
together and the back story

00:30:52.330 --> 00:30:55.150
of Bhiku Mhatre about
literally little things--

00:30:55.150 --> 00:30:58.630
if I tell you, if you
remember the film--

00:30:58.630 --> 00:31:04.120
like when I get into
the house of Bhau, who

00:31:04.120 --> 00:31:08.600
was just played by Govind
Namdeo, I touched his feet.

00:31:08.600 --> 00:31:13.160
So Ram asked me, why
did you touch his feet?

00:31:13.160 --> 00:31:18.000
So I said, in my back story,
after my father's death,

00:31:18.000 --> 00:31:21.750
he is somebody who helped
my mother, to bring me up.

00:31:21.750 --> 00:31:23.870
And that's how I
am with him today.

00:31:23.870 --> 00:31:25.910
I'm working for him.

00:31:25.910 --> 00:31:28.320
So for me, he's like
a father figure.

00:31:28.320 --> 00:31:31.390
Oh, let me go for
a close-up then.

00:31:31.390 --> 00:31:33.340
So he took a close-up of that.

00:31:33.340 --> 00:31:36.400
So that's how Bhiku
Mhatre kept on happening,

00:31:36.400 --> 00:31:39.260
kept on shaping up everyday.

00:31:39.260 --> 00:31:42.370
It's never one person's effort.

00:31:42.370 --> 00:31:44.470
It's very collective.

00:31:44.470 --> 00:31:47.170
Sometimes directors
are so welcoming.

00:31:47.170 --> 00:31:48.940
And they keep adding
little, little things

00:31:48.940 --> 00:31:52.310
to your preparation,
which is amazing.

00:31:52.310 --> 00:31:57.820
And Sardar Khan-- when
I was hearing the script

00:31:57.820 --> 00:32:01.720
from Anurag Kashyap,
he said, Bajpayee, I

00:32:01.720 --> 00:32:04.110
don't want to see
Bhiku Mhatre in this.

00:32:04.110 --> 00:32:06.060
I said, this guy is not a mafia.

00:32:06.060 --> 00:32:07.660
He said, no, no, he's a mafia.

00:32:07.660 --> 00:32:10.840
I know, and for me,
he's a womanizer.

00:32:10.840 --> 00:32:16.270
So I have never treated Sardar
Khan as a dangerous guy.

00:32:16.270 --> 00:32:22.060
I treated him as somebody who
is always looking for cheap sex

00:32:22.060 --> 00:32:23.090
all the time.

00:32:23.090 --> 00:32:27.190
So if you see the film,
that's how I prepared myself.

00:32:27.190 --> 00:32:31.510
Even the body, the
raw sex appeal.

00:32:31.510 --> 00:32:34.950
I went for-- well,
I requested, Anurag,

00:32:34.950 --> 00:32:40.790
please allow me to
have a bald head.

00:32:40.790 --> 00:32:42.627
And for a few days,
he was not ready.

00:32:42.627 --> 00:32:44.710
And suddenly one fine
morning, he got up, he said,

00:32:44.710 --> 00:32:47.590
Bajpayee, let's go for it.

00:32:47.590 --> 00:32:52.060
So we have done everything
possible which could actually

00:32:52.060 --> 00:32:55.240
enhance his raw sex appeal.

00:32:55.240 --> 00:33:01.120
And also, the way
he walks, the way

00:33:01.120 --> 00:33:04.180
he talks to a woman, the
way he looks at a woman

00:33:04.180 --> 00:33:07.730
is not something I
have ever experienced.

00:33:07.730 --> 00:33:11.230
So to get into the
zone, in one shot,

00:33:11.230 --> 00:33:13.750
Anurag Kashyap said,
Durga is sitting there.

00:33:13.750 --> 00:33:14.650
She's making roti.

00:33:14.650 --> 00:33:18.202
And you have to look at her
in the most perverse way.

00:33:18.202 --> 00:33:21.580
[AUDIENCE LAUGHING]

00:33:21.580 --> 00:33:27.940
And that shot has become
quite a landmark for people.

00:33:27.940 --> 00:33:30.370
And they keep asking me,
how could you do that?

00:33:30.370 --> 00:33:33.849
[AUDIENCE LAUGHING]

00:33:34.850 --> 00:33:38.720
So yes, for that, you
have to be an actor.

00:33:38.720 --> 00:33:41.612
[AUDIENCE LAUGHING]

00:33:41.612 --> 00:33:44.504
[LAUGHING]

00:33:44.504 --> 00:33:49.150
I know, because there
are certain reactions.

00:33:52.200 --> 00:33:57.630
Every good actor, like
[INAUDIBLE] is sitting here--

00:33:57.630 --> 00:34:00.639
in many ways, she's my senior.

00:34:00.639 --> 00:34:02.180
And she will agree
with me that there

00:34:02.180 --> 00:34:05.480
are many, many of the actions
that an actor achieves,

00:34:05.480 --> 00:34:09.529
and sometimes even actor doesn't
know that it actually happened.

00:34:09.529 --> 00:34:11.659
It actually-- it just happened.

00:34:11.659 --> 00:34:13.280
It just happened in that shot.

00:34:13.280 --> 00:34:14.510
It just happened.

00:34:14.510 --> 00:34:17.120
And everybody clapped.

00:34:17.120 --> 00:34:19.719
And every actor has this memory.

00:34:19.719 --> 00:34:23.895
And for that shot, I realize--

00:34:23.895 --> 00:34:27.104
I remember Anurag Kashyap
looking at the monitor.

00:34:27.104 --> 00:34:30.230
And he said cut, and
he came and hugged me.

00:34:30.230 --> 00:34:33.639
And it just happened.

00:34:33.639 --> 00:34:36.469
And if you asked me how
could I manage to do it?

00:34:36.469 --> 00:34:38.659
The most perverse reaction?

00:34:38.659 --> 00:34:40.670
Believe me, I have
never chased a girl.

00:34:40.670 --> 00:34:43.750
[AUDIENCE LAUGHING]

00:34:43.750 --> 00:34:49.610
As a small village boy, I was
very scared of telling a girl,

00:34:49.610 --> 00:34:50.586
"I like you."

00:34:50.586 --> 00:34:52.460
I always thought that
she's going to slap me.

00:34:52.460 --> 00:34:53.251
[AUDIENCE LAUGHING]

00:34:53.251 --> 00:34:57.110
So for many years, I
couldn't date a girl.

00:34:57.110 --> 00:35:00.470
So you are talking
to a person who

00:35:00.470 --> 00:35:05.330
has this kind of a life story
and who has done Sardar Khan!

00:35:05.330 --> 00:35:06.920
For me, he's quite
an achievement!

00:35:06.920 --> 00:35:10.121
[LAUGHING]

00:35:10.620 --> 00:35:13.520
SPEAKER 1: So it was interesting
to learn how you distinguish

00:35:13.520 --> 00:35:15.860
Bhiku Mhatre being a
gangster and Sardar Khan

00:35:15.860 --> 00:35:17.390
being a womanizer.

00:35:17.390 --> 00:35:20.900
What was your
character from "Aks"?

00:35:20.900 --> 00:35:23.900
What were you thinking
of him in these terms?

00:35:23.900 --> 00:35:25.520
How did you think
of his back story?

00:35:25.520 --> 00:35:27.816
MANOJ BAJPAYEE: Rakeysh Mehra--

00:35:27.816 --> 00:35:29.480
he told me about the script.

00:35:29.480 --> 00:35:32.690
And then he said,
I don't want you

00:35:32.690 --> 00:35:34.580
to play character in this film.

00:35:34.580 --> 00:35:37.150
I want you to play evil.

00:35:37.150 --> 00:35:40.520
So evil is a metaphor.

00:35:40.520 --> 00:35:46.170
If I tell an actor,
you have to play evil--

00:35:46.170 --> 00:35:48.980
now, evil has too
many facets to it.

00:35:48.980 --> 00:35:52.560
You can't just say
that evil is dangerous.

00:35:52.560 --> 00:35:55.730
Evil is most flamboyant.

00:35:55.730 --> 00:35:58.837
Evil is most attractive.

00:36:01.980 --> 00:36:06.660
A bottle of liquor is far
more fascinating looking than

00:36:06.660 --> 00:36:10.770
a bottle of
[NON-ENGLISH SPEECH],, right?

00:36:10.770 --> 00:36:13.710
So why they make it
fascinating looking?

00:36:13.710 --> 00:36:18.610
So that you buy it,
and you drink it.

00:36:18.610 --> 00:36:26.560
And if you get lured
very easily by any bar--

00:36:26.560 --> 00:36:31.300
but when you get into a
bar, it's all dark, dungeon.

00:36:31.300 --> 00:36:34.750
You don't know when you're
going to come out of it.

00:36:34.750 --> 00:36:35.960
You want to come out.

00:36:35.960 --> 00:36:38.560
You want to say, this is
the time I should go back.

00:36:38.560 --> 00:36:40.270
This is a time I should
go back to sleep.

00:36:40.270 --> 00:36:42.130
But you don't come out.

00:36:42.130 --> 00:36:43.260
You keep on dancing.

00:36:43.260 --> 00:36:46.410
You keep on drinking.

00:36:46.410 --> 00:36:47.690
So that's evil.

00:36:47.690 --> 00:36:52.130
So that was my point for the
characterization of "Aks."

00:36:52.130 --> 00:36:57.130
So if you see the film,
he's very flamboyant.

00:36:57.130 --> 00:36:59.940
He's a very good lover.

00:36:59.940 --> 00:37:01.130
He's very attractive.

00:37:01.130 --> 00:37:03.470
That's why the long hair was.

00:37:03.470 --> 00:37:05.610
He is sharp.

00:37:05.610 --> 00:37:08.550
But there is something very,
very dangerous about him.

00:37:08.550 --> 00:37:11.670
And that something
you only get to know

00:37:11.670 --> 00:37:13.590
when he starts laughing.

00:37:13.590 --> 00:37:17.520
That is the only sign where you
realize that this guy is not

00:37:17.520 --> 00:37:19.330
trustworthy.

00:37:19.330 --> 00:37:25.320
So that's how two, three
months of preparation

00:37:25.320 --> 00:37:28.362
has gone into making Raghavan.

00:37:28.362 --> 00:37:30.570
SPEAKER 1: I think we have
another audience question.

00:37:30.570 --> 00:37:31.470
AUDIENCE: Hi, Manoj.

00:37:31.470 --> 00:37:32.500
My name is [INAUDIBLE].

00:37:32.500 --> 00:37:34.230
I'm a huge fan of you.

00:37:34.230 --> 00:37:38.250
So my question is, these
days, a lot of period films,

00:37:38.250 --> 00:37:41.250
biographies are
coming in Bollywood.

00:37:41.250 --> 00:37:44.610
And you do a lot of research,
a lot of hard work for it all.

00:37:44.610 --> 00:37:48.180
So is there any famous figure
or historical personality

00:37:48.180 --> 00:37:51.330
you easily identify with
yourself, and you have a dream,

00:37:51.330 --> 00:37:54.144
or you want to play
that character?

00:37:54.144 --> 00:37:54.810
Do you have any?

00:37:54.810 --> 00:37:56.240
MANOJ BAJPAYEE: I would
like to play Chanakya.

00:37:56.240 --> 00:37:56.943
AUDIENCE: Chanakya?

00:37:56.943 --> 00:37:59.109
MANOJ BAJPAYEE: Yeah, I
would like to play Chanakya.

00:37:59.109 --> 00:38:04.620
I really feel that he's the
biggest philosopher of all.

00:38:04.620 --> 00:38:06.240
And he's not been
read until now.

00:38:06.240 --> 00:38:09.060
[AUDIENCE APPLAUSE]

00:38:09.060 --> 00:38:14.760
That will give me a chance to
really do research on Chanakya,

00:38:14.760 --> 00:38:17.710
who is known as Kautilya.

00:38:17.710 --> 00:38:21.540
So that will also give me a
chance to know all the text,

00:38:21.540 --> 00:38:23.260
know everything about him.

00:38:23.260 --> 00:38:26.130
Because whatever little
that I know of him,

00:38:26.130 --> 00:38:30.447
I think he's somebody who should
get his due by the filmmakers.

00:38:30.447 --> 00:38:31.280
AUDIENCE: Thank you.

00:38:34.850 --> 00:38:36.624
SPEAKER 1: Another audience?

00:38:36.624 --> 00:38:37.290
AUDIENCE: Hello.

00:38:37.290 --> 00:38:40.560
This is more of a complaint.

00:38:40.560 --> 00:38:44.330
There are movies like
"Gangs of Wasseypur,"

00:38:44.330 --> 00:38:46.550
"Aligarh," "Budhia
Singh" that did not get

00:38:46.550 --> 00:38:47.665
released in the Bay Area.

00:38:47.665 --> 00:38:50.040
MANOJ BAJPAYEE: You are going
to talk something which I'm

00:38:50.040 --> 00:38:51.340
going to answer very brutally.

00:38:51.340 --> 00:38:52.131
[AUDIENCE LAUGHING]

00:38:52.131 --> 00:38:53.220
AUDIENCE: Yes.

00:38:53.220 --> 00:38:55.630
And then you made a
very fine distinction

00:38:55.630 --> 00:38:58.750
that there's a difference
between an actor and a star.

00:38:58.750 --> 00:39:01.470
The star gets all the
money, the actor doesn't.

00:39:01.470 --> 00:39:06.850
So what are you as an actor
trying to do to become a star?

00:39:06.850 --> 00:39:09.740
MANOJ BAJPAYEE: See, you
have to understand one thing.

00:39:09.740 --> 00:39:10.990
AUDIENCE: Can I say something?

00:39:10.990 --> 00:39:11.690
MANOJ BAJPAYEE: Yeah, please.

00:39:11.690 --> 00:39:13.148
AUDIENCE: I think
Manoj is probably

00:39:13.148 --> 00:39:16.055
one of those rare examples of
an actor who is truly a star.

00:39:16.055 --> 00:39:17.397
[AUDIENCE APPLAUSE]

00:39:17.397 --> 00:39:18.480
MANOJ BAJPAYEE: Thank you!

00:39:18.480 --> 00:39:19.450
Thank you.

00:39:23.480 --> 00:39:27.260
A star is when-- you
don't become a star.

00:39:27.260 --> 00:39:30.200
I really feel that way.

00:39:30.200 --> 00:39:33.090
Stardom just happens to you.

00:39:33.090 --> 00:39:41.640
But actor-- you have to really
work hard to become an actor.

00:39:41.640 --> 00:39:44.400
You can't work
hard to be a star.

00:39:44.400 --> 00:39:52.680
Stardom is not something which
can be achieved by hard work.

00:39:52.680 --> 00:39:53.640
All you can do is--

00:39:53.640 --> 00:39:56.430
but I wanted to be part
of these kind of films.

00:39:56.430 --> 00:40:03.390
I always saw a dream where I'll
be playing these roles which

00:40:03.390 --> 00:40:06.730
are in of our day to day life.

00:40:06.730 --> 00:40:09.802
And they are the
heroes, whether it is

00:40:09.802 --> 00:40:11.430
Biranchi Das of "Budhia Singh."

00:40:13.980 --> 00:40:16.975
When the news of "Budhia
Sing" was coming out,

00:40:16.975 --> 00:40:18.630
and he is going to
run the marathon,

00:40:18.630 --> 00:40:22.260
it was covered widely
by all the channels.

00:40:22.260 --> 00:40:27.780
And I was quite fascinated
by this coach who was--

00:40:27.780 --> 00:40:33.300
swich on one channel, he is
being regarded as the villain

00:40:33.300 --> 00:40:34.140
by one channel.

00:40:34.140 --> 00:40:37.980
And he is being regarded as
hero on the other channel.

00:40:37.980 --> 00:40:39.390
So that interested me.

00:40:39.390 --> 00:40:43.410
I said, what a
personality this man is!

00:40:43.410 --> 00:40:47.540
He's such a
contradiction in himself.

00:40:47.540 --> 00:40:50.290
Whenever I saw him
talking about Budhia,

00:40:50.290 --> 00:40:54.852
I also saw a very arrogant
man and a very innocent man.

00:40:54.852 --> 00:40:59.100
So this combination of arrogance
and innocence of Biranchi Das

00:40:59.100 --> 00:41:01.472
really attracted me.

00:41:01.472 --> 00:41:03.930
And when I was offered this
role, I immediately grabbed it.

00:41:03.930 --> 00:41:07.310
I said, I must do this role.

00:41:07.310 --> 00:41:09.030
There is a dream.

00:41:09.030 --> 00:41:16.130
There is a dream that one
day, entire Indian audience

00:41:16.130 --> 00:41:21.150
through all the world
will be standing

00:41:21.150 --> 00:41:24.060
in queue to watch these films.

00:41:24.060 --> 00:41:25.770
There is a dream.

00:41:25.770 --> 00:41:31.630
And I'm working on these films
with the dream in my mind.

00:41:31.630 --> 00:41:32.730
It's not happening.

00:41:32.730 --> 00:41:35.980
Our audience is failing
us all the time.

00:41:35.980 --> 00:41:39.458
It's not the producers
who are failing us.

00:41:39.458 --> 00:41:41.810
It's the audience
who is failing us.

00:41:41.810 --> 00:41:44.290
But should we fail ourselves?

00:41:44.290 --> 00:41:46.160
No.

00:41:46.160 --> 00:41:49.060
We can't afford
to fail ourselves.

00:41:49.060 --> 00:41:53.020
We can only go on doing
what we believe in.

00:41:53.020 --> 00:41:58.480
We should go on
doing things that

00:41:58.480 --> 00:42:01.330
will one day fulfill our dream.

00:42:01.330 --> 00:42:02.600
Now, that dream doesn't die.

00:42:02.600 --> 00:42:05.890
Dream only dies when
[NON-ENGLISH] people die.

00:42:05.890 --> 00:42:07.300
This dream will always be there.

00:42:07.300 --> 00:42:09.140
[AUDIENCE APPLAUSE]

00:42:11.170 --> 00:42:16.180
Like you stand in queue and buy
the first day for sure ticket

00:42:16.180 --> 00:42:17.950
for [NON-ENGLISH] film.

00:42:17.950 --> 00:42:22.030
The dream is there that one
day, you'll be standing in queue

00:42:22.030 --> 00:42:24.340
and buying the first
day for sure ticket

00:42:24.340 --> 00:42:26.530
for those content-driven films.

00:42:26.530 --> 00:42:28.270
That dream is there.

00:42:28.270 --> 00:42:34.630
And so many actors, so many
filmmakers are working on it.

00:42:34.630 --> 00:42:38.000
They have the choice and options
of making other kind of films.

00:42:38.000 --> 00:42:40.750
But no, their
belief is into this.

00:42:40.750 --> 00:42:42.780
And kudos to them.

00:42:42.780 --> 00:42:45.460
They sacrifice so many other--

00:42:45.460 --> 00:42:49.470
there are so many other
comfortable things to do this.

00:42:49.470 --> 00:42:56.040
So the day audience
will wake up,

00:42:56.040 --> 00:42:58.320
the day they start
going to the theater

00:42:58.320 --> 00:43:03.630
to watch these films, that
will be the day you will start

00:43:03.630 --> 00:43:08.670
seeing a different
kind of a change coming

00:43:08.670 --> 00:43:09.960
in the Indian industry.

00:43:09.960 --> 00:43:13.470
And then Indian industry
will become a global force.

00:43:13.470 --> 00:43:16.410
Because until the time we
are not focusing on content,

00:43:16.410 --> 00:43:20.118
we can't compete with
the world cinema.

00:43:20.118 --> 00:43:24.405
We will always be
regarded as Bollywood.

